1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,880
Okay, so

2
00:00:01,880 --> 00:00:05,020
last class we talked about Maria Kumbotas,

3
00:00:05,240 --> 00:00:07,000
who is an anthropologist.

4
00:00:07,280 --> 00:00:09,540
And she makes the argument that

5
00:00:09,540 --> 00:00:12,100
for the longest time,

6
00:00:12,140 --> 00:00:16,100
for most of its history,
Europe was egalitarian,

7
00:00:16,460 --> 00:00:18,000
peaceful,

8
00:00:18,460 --> 00:00:22,120
and artistic. But

9
00:00:22,120 --> 00:00:26,500
today, we are a patriarchy.

10
00:00:28,520 --> 00:00:29,760
There's a lot of inequality,

11
00:00:30,280 --> 00:00:33,520
and we're always at war with each other.

12
00:00:33,820 --> 00:00:35,940
So what changed? And

13
00:00:35,940 --> 00:00:39,360
last time we discussed

14
00:00:39,360 --> 00:00:41,220
that

15
00:00:41,220 --> 00:00:47,120
old Europe was conquered
by a warlike people,

16
00:00:47,360 --> 00:00:49,680
who we call today the Yemeniah.

17
00:00:50,600 --> 00:00:54,140
So three questions I want to
answer in today's class is,

18
00:00:54,300 --> 00:00:55,500
first of all,

19
00:00:56,500 --> 00:00:57,860
who are the Yemeniah?

20
00:00:58,160 --> 00:00:59,500
Second question is,

21
00:01:00,300 --> 00:01:01,720
where did they come from?

22
00:01:02,260 --> 00:01:05,840
And the third question is,
how did they conquer Europe?

23
00:01:06,260 --> 00:01:08,360
Alright, so

24
00:01:08,360 --> 00:01:11,740
let's go back in time

25
00:01:11,740 --> 00:01:17,420
and look at the world
about 10,000 years ago.

26
00:01:17,640 --> 00:01:22,360
So we believe that about 11,000
years ago, in the Near East,

27
00:01:25,020 --> 00:01:26,960
we developed agriculture.

28
00:01:27,960 --> 00:01:30,900
We developed the technology of farming.

29
00:01:31,120 --> 00:01:35,460
And as we discussed in
our very first class,

30
00:01:35,720 --> 00:01:39,360
it was because humans
are a religious people.

31
00:01:40,220 --> 00:01:44,380
And farming allows us to
celebrate our religion.

32
00:01:45,080 --> 00:01:49,760
And the reason why farming was
founded in the Near East is,

33
00:01:49,760 --> 00:01:53,260
for the longest time, there's an ice age.

34
00:01:54,060 --> 00:01:55,260
So you couldn't farm.

35
00:01:55,640 --> 00:02:00,260
You had to move around
from place to place to hunt

36
00:02:00,260 --> 00:02:01,840
and find food.

37
00:02:02,260 --> 00:02:05,880
So after the ice age, which
ended about 12,000 years ago,

38
00:02:06,580 --> 00:02:08,880
the climate became warmer, and

39
00:02:08,880 --> 00:02:12,220
the Near East became the area where

40
00:02:12,220 --> 00:02:14,480
you could grow crops, the easiest.

41
00:02:15,200 --> 00:02:18,160
So Near East is what we
call the Middle East today,

42
00:02:18,280 --> 00:02:20,720
which includes Turkey, Jordan,

43
00:02:21,140 --> 00:02:22,880
Syria, and Israel.

44
00:02:23,020 --> 00:02:25,540
That's where farming was invented.

45
00:02:28,440 --> 00:02:32,180
About 7,000, 8,000 years ago,

46
00:02:32,280 --> 00:02:35,030
the weather became a lot cooler.

47
00:02:35,460 --> 00:02:39,280
There was another ice age for a
very short amount of time. And

48
00:02:39,280 --> 00:02:42,740
this forced people to start to immigrate

49
00:02:42,740 --> 00:02:45,480
or migrate to look for new land.

50
00:02:46,060 --> 00:02:49,640
So people in the Near East,
they went off to Europe,

51
00:02:51,520 --> 00:02:54,640
and these people were very lucky,

52
00:02:54,760 --> 00:02:59,400
because the geography of Europe was not

53
00:02:59,400 --> 00:03:02,260
that different from the
geography of the Near East.

54
00:03:02,460 --> 00:03:05,820
So they could take their religion,
they could take their technology,

55
00:03:06,060 --> 00:03:09,040
move over to Europe, and

56
00:03:09,040 --> 00:03:11,620
still be about the same.

57
00:03:11,720 --> 00:03:12,960
There were some minor changes,

58
00:03:13,600 --> 00:03:15,320
but they were more or less the same.

59
00:03:15,840 --> 00:03:17,260
So these people were very lucky.

60
00:03:17,640 --> 00:03:20,580
And these people, as Maria Kambuta said,

61
00:03:20,940 --> 00:03:25,260
these people have the same religion
as the people of the Near East.

62
00:03:25,560 --> 00:03:29,400
They worship the Mother Goddess,
who gives life to everything.

63
00:03:29,780 --> 00:03:32,760
They believe in the ideas of unity.

64
00:03:33,840 --> 00:03:37,040
Unity just means that we are the same.

65
00:03:37,220 --> 00:03:38,880
Every one of us are the same.

66
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:42,920
We have a responsibility to love each
other, and to love each other's children.

67
00:03:43,940 --> 00:03:45,460
We're the same as animals.

68
00:03:45,680 --> 00:03:50,420
We're the same as plants. So we
must do our best to protect nature.

69
00:03:50,960 --> 00:03:53,800
The farms allow us to eat food, but

70
00:03:53,800 --> 00:03:55,900
we should not destroy nature.

71
00:03:56,060 --> 00:03:58,860
We should protect nature, because
it's all the Mother Goddess.

72
00:03:59,200 --> 00:04:01,260
We're all the children
of the Mother Goddess.

73
00:04:01,960 --> 00:04:06,680
So we also believe in balance and harmony.

74
00:04:06,980 --> 00:04:09,620
And this is the religion,
as we discussed before,

75
00:04:10,400 --> 00:04:13,720
of many indigenous
peoples around the world.

76
00:04:13,820 --> 00:04:15,360
If you go to Africa, Australia,

77
00:04:17,540 --> 00:04:20,740
the Amazon, and you meet
these indigenous peoples,

78
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:22,820
they have the same religion,

79
00:04:23,680 --> 00:04:25,920
which is, we come from a Mother Goddess,

80
00:04:26,480 --> 00:04:30,700
and we have a responsibility
to protect the nature,

81
00:04:31,480 --> 00:04:35,800
the earth, because that's the
gift from the Mother Goddess.

82
00:04:36,320 --> 00:04:37,640
And everyone has a soul.

83
00:04:37,860 --> 00:04:42,020
So after we die, our soul still lives on.

84
00:04:42,360 --> 00:04:44,520
Does that make sense, guys? So

85
00:04:44,520 --> 00:04:47,600
this is the religion of old Europe.

86
00:04:47,700 --> 00:04:50,000
And because of this religion,
they were egalitarian,

87
00:04:50,340 --> 00:04:53,500
meaning there was no real
difference between men and women.

88
00:04:53,660 --> 00:04:57,180
In fact, because women had
the power to give birth,

89
00:04:57,360 --> 00:05:02,120
to give life, they were considered
in many ways superior to men.

90
00:05:02,240 --> 00:05:06,240
And the political class was
mainly governed by women.

91
00:05:06,380 --> 00:05:09,700
Okay? They were peaceful.

92
00:05:09,800 --> 00:05:11,860
They really didn't have to
fight each other, because

93
00:05:11,860 --> 00:05:15,720
they felt their resources
was enough for them.

94
00:05:15,880 --> 00:05:17,760
Okay? And they were artistic. So

95
00:05:17,760 --> 00:05:21,200
they focused their
intellectual energies on

96
00:05:21,200 --> 00:05:24,760
creating art to celebrate the
Mother Goddess and their religion.

97
00:05:24,980 --> 00:05:28,380
Okay? So the people of the Near East

98
00:05:28,380 --> 00:05:30,760
and the people of Europe
were very similar.

99
00:05:30,900 --> 00:05:35,380
Okay? The problem starts
when these people went off to

100
00:05:36,380 --> 00:05:38,400
what we call the steppes.

101
00:05:39,060 --> 00:05:43,520
The steppes is a huge ocean of grassland

102
00:05:43,520 --> 00:05:48,180
that basically extends
from Europe into Mongolia.

103
00:05:48,500 --> 00:05:51,920
Okay? And you know, the Chinese
word for this is taoyuan.

104
00:05:52,200 --> 00:05:55,840
Now the problem with the

105
00:05:55,840 --> 00:05:59,040
grassland is people can't eat grass.

106
00:05:59,500 --> 00:06:03,600
And you cannot grow crops on grassland

107
00:06:03,600 --> 00:06:04,940
that easily. Okay?

108
00:06:05,460 --> 00:06:08,760
So the people on the steppes,

109
00:06:08,760 --> 00:06:10,720
they struggle to survive.

110
00:06:10,720 --> 00:06:14,820
And the people on the steppes

111
00:06:15,640 --> 00:06:20,160
engage in a process we
call social evolution.

112
00:06:21,880 --> 00:06:25,080
Okay? So you may have
heard the term evolution.

113
00:06:25,760 --> 00:06:30,040
I want to explain what the term
evolution means for our class,

114
00:06:30,260 --> 00:06:34,820
because we will refer to it a lot as
we progress through human history.

115
00:06:34,900 --> 00:06:39,000
Okay? So for us, evolution means open

116
00:06:44,180 --> 00:06:46,100
cooperative competition.

117
00:06:48,080 --> 00:06:52,000
Okay? So this is what evolution means.

118
00:06:52,380 --> 00:06:53,340
And

119
00:06:53,340 --> 00:06:57,400
evolution has historically been the

120
00:06:57,400 --> 00:07:01,200
greatest source of human
innovation and creativity.

121
00:07:01,540 --> 00:07:03,140
Okay? So let me explain why.

122
00:07:04,360 --> 00:07:07,980
Open means there's no central authority.

123
00:07:08,380 --> 00:07:09,740
There's no great power.

124
00:07:09,900 --> 00:07:13,000
Okay? There's no hegemon. Everyone's
competing against each other.

125
00:07:14,040 --> 00:07:17,020
Competition just means these people,

126
00:07:18,660 --> 00:07:22,880
these many different people, they're
trying to compete to survive.

127
00:07:23,360 --> 00:07:26,820
Okay? There are very scarce
resources in the steppes.

128
00:07:26,880 --> 00:07:29,780
It's not as wealthy as the
Near East and as Europe.

129
00:07:30,000 --> 00:07:31,400
And they're all trying to survive.

130
00:07:31,780 --> 00:07:35,000
They all adopt different
strategies in order to survive.

131
00:07:35,320 --> 00:07:37,340
Okay? At the same time,

132
00:07:37,500 --> 00:07:42,140
cooperative means they're still
communicating with each other.

133
00:07:42,280 --> 00:07:44,700
They're still trading.
They're still friends.

134
00:07:45,020 --> 00:07:47,780
Maybe they'll exchange wives,

135
00:07:48,140 --> 00:07:50,400
exchange presents. So

136
00:07:50,400 --> 00:07:55,460
this is a process of social evolution

137
00:07:55,460 --> 00:07:59,300
that has created the most
innovation in human history.

138
00:07:59,520 --> 00:08:01,220
So in Chinese history,

139
00:08:02,840 --> 00:08:06,060
this most resembles what
period in Chinese history?

140
00:08:07,320 --> 00:08:10,420
In Chinese history. Which

141
00:08:10,420 --> 00:08:13,040
part of Chinese history
does this process where

142
00:08:13,040 --> 00:08:16,320
you have many different people

143
00:08:17,160 --> 00:08:21,280
in open competition with each other
but still learning from each other?

144
00:08:21,500 --> 00:08:22,820
This period in Chinese history is called?

145
00:08:25,860 --> 00:08:28,900
Exactly, right? And that's where

146
00:08:28,900 --> 00:08:33,160
most of Chinese innovation and
creativity came from, from that period.

147
00:08:33,420 --> 00:08:36,400
Confucius came from that
period. Laozi, okay?

148
00:08:36,480 --> 00:08:39,840
A lot of major intellectual
breakthroughs came from that period.

149
00:08:40,420 --> 00:08:42,260
Okay? But

150
00:08:42,260 --> 00:08:46,000
not only the Chunchiu of China.

151
00:08:47,280 --> 00:08:48,480
As we move on,

152
00:08:48,840 --> 00:08:51,440
we will also look at two
other major periods where

153
00:08:51,440 --> 00:08:54,300
there was a major outburst of innovation

154
00:08:54,920 --> 00:08:59,280
and then very similar social
structure as like this, okay?

155
00:08:59,520 --> 00:09:03,360
So we will also be studying
the Greek city -states.

156
00:09:05,180 --> 00:09:08,940
In fact, we will spend a lot of time
on the Greek city -states like Athens

157
00:09:08,940 --> 00:09:11,880
and Sparta and Thebes because

158
00:09:11,880 --> 00:09:13,640
before,

159
00:09:13,900 --> 00:09:17,220
we actually thought the origin
of Western civilization

160
00:09:18,380 --> 00:09:20,040
were the Greek city -states, okay?

161
00:09:20,160 --> 00:09:22,560
We no longer believe that,
but for the longest time,

162
00:09:22,720 --> 00:09:27,040
we believe Western civilization
came from the Greek city -states.

163
00:09:27,140 --> 00:09:28,880
And when we look at
the Greek city -states,

164
00:09:28,880 --> 00:09:32,260
you will discover the system they had back

165
00:09:32,260 --> 00:09:35,300
then is very similar to this system, okay?

166
00:09:37,260 --> 00:09:42,700
We will also look at the
Sumerian city -states,

167
00:09:45,640 --> 00:09:48,620
okay? Which is very similar
to the Greek city -states.

168
00:09:50,600 --> 00:09:52,240
Yes, okay? So

169
00:09:52,240 --> 00:09:57,400
we will be studying
these different periods,

170
00:09:57,660 --> 00:09:59,380
okay? But I want you to remember,

171
00:09:59,600 --> 00:10:05,480
the first important principle is whenever
there is an open cooperative competition,

172
00:10:06,040 --> 00:10:08,880
tremendous innovation happens, okay?

173
00:10:09,080 --> 00:10:12,020
That's the first principle
I want you to remember.

174
00:10:12,640 --> 00:10:15,140
The second principle I
want you to remember is

175
00:10:15,720 --> 00:10:19,900
eventually, someone triumphs
in this competition,

176
00:10:20,240 --> 00:10:21,560
okay?

177
00:10:21,720 --> 00:10:23,820
And the group, the people

178
00:10:23,820 --> 00:10:25,800
that

179
00:10:25,800 --> 00:10:28,760
triumphs are the people who

180
00:10:28,760 --> 00:10:30,960
are most,

181
00:10:30,960 --> 00:10:35,460
most open to adopting innovation

182
00:10:36,700 --> 00:10:39,500
in order to destroy others, okay?

183
00:10:39,520 --> 00:10:44,560
Does that make sense? They are the most
ruthless in adopting all innovations

184
00:10:45,440 --> 00:10:48,940
for the sole purpose of destroying others

185
00:10:48,940 --> 00:10:50,980
and becoming the sole hegemon, okay?

186
00:10:51,220 --> 00:10:54,320
So we saw this with the
Greek city -states where

187
00:10:54,320 --> 00:10:58,920
for hundreds of years, they were
in competition with each other.

188
00:10:59,180 --> 00:11:00,600
And then there was a,

189
00:11:01,140 --> 00:11:03,160
a group of people called the Macedonians

190
00:11:05,940 --> 00:11:07,840
who weren't actually Greek, okay?

191
00:11:08,200 --> 00:11:13,960
They were marginal to
the Greek city -states.

192
00:11:14,020 --> 00:11:18,480
And the Greeks didn't really consider the
Macedonians part of their civilization.

193
00:11:19,160 --> 00:11:23,440
But they were on the outskirts and
they observed all the innovations

194
00:11:23,940 --> 00:11:27,120
that the Greek city -states were creating,
especially in terms of military innovation,

195
00:11:27,500 --> 00:11:30,460
adopted all innovations
for their purposes, and

196
00:11:30,460 --> 00:11:33,820
then conquered the city
-states before they moved on

197
00:11:33,820 --> 00:11:37,420
and conquered Persia and Egypt, okay?

198
00:11:37,740 --> 00:11:41,840
And the leader of the Macedonians
was called, do you guys know?

199
00:11:43,900 --> 00:11:47,680
Who was the leader of the Macedonians
who conquered the Greek city -states?

200
00:11:48,900 --> 00:11:52,800
I'm sure you know who he is, but you
may not know he was a Macedonian.

201
00:11:55,180 --> 00:11:57,200
Who's the most famous
Greek you've heard of?

202
00:12:00,540 --> 00:12:02,660
Yeah, he was actually Macedonian, okay?

203
00:12:03,540 --> 00:12:09,120
Alexander the Great. Okay? And

204
00:12:09,120 --> 00:12:12,740
what's amazing is we see the same

205
00:12:12,740 --> 00:12:16,320
pattern play out with the
Sumerian city -states,

206
00:12:16,420 --> 00:12:18,380
where for a hundred years,

207
00:12:18,780 --> 00:12:21,500
the city -states were in
competition with each other.

208
00:12:21,580 --> 00:12:24,540
They were all trying to conquer
each other without success.

209
00:12:24,920 --> 00:12:29,260
And then an outside people, a
neighbor called the Akkadians,

210
00:12:29,260 --> 00:12:30,640
the Akkadians,

211
00:12:33,960 --> 00:12:36,720
they adopted all the innovation and

212
00:12:36,720 --> 00:12:39,980
technology of the Sumerian
city -states, and

213
00:12:39,980 --> 00:12:42,880
then they conquered the
Sumerian city -states and

214
00:12:42,880 --> 00:12:47,340
established the first great world
empire called the Akkadian Empire.

215
00:12:47,700 --> 00:12:51,980
And the founder of that empire, we
will learn, is called Sargon the Great.

216
00:12:52,180 --> 00:12:54,400
Okay? Sargon the Great.

217
00:12:54,560 --> 00:12:59,180
And Sargon the Great is considered
the world's very first empire builder.

218
00:12:59,260 --> 00:13:01,520
So even though

219
00:13:01,520 --> 00:13:05,840
we know almost nothing about
what was happening here,

220
00:13:06,100 --> 00:13:09,540
from our knowledge of
the Greek city -states

221
00:13:09,540 --> 00:13:14,460
and the Sumerian city -states

222
00:13:14,460 --> 00:13:20,380
and what happened to them, we can guess or
hypothesize the same process played out here

223
00:13:20,380 --> 00:13:22,360
where these different tribes,

224
00:13:22,480 --> 00:13:25,300
these different groups were creating
all sorts of different innovations.

225
00:13:25,740 --> 00:13:30,500
Then one outside group came in, adopted all
the innovations, and then conquered everyone.

226
00:13:30,800 --> 00:13:34,100
Okay? And these people are
what we call the Anaya,

227
00:13:37,180 --> 00:13:40,520
who originated, we believe, in Ukraine.

228
00:13:40,800 --> 00:13:44,240
Okay? So let's now discuss the innovations

229
00:13:45,040 --> 00:13:47,100
that these people created.

230
00:13:47,240 --> 00:13:49,980
Okay? And the innovations
were pretty incredible because

231
00:13:49,980 --> 00:13:52,200
they forever transformed human history.

232
00:13:52,620 --> 00:13:55,700
Okay, so the first innovation they adopted

233
00:13:56,180 --> 00:13:57,900
was a pastoral economy.

234
00:13:58,040 --> 00:14:00,840
Okay? So basically, the pastoral economy,

235
00:14:01,100 --> 00:14:04,720
basically raising cattle,
raising or herding cattle,

236
00:14:04,840 --> 00:14:06,240
or cows.

237
00:14:07,920 --> 00:14:10,820
All right. So

238
00:14:10,820 --> 00:14:13,140
we cannot eat grass, okay?

239
00:14:14,140 --> 00:14:17,100
But cows and sheep and

240
00:14:17,100 --> 00:14:21,060
goats can eat grass, and
then we can eat the cows,

241
00:14:21,380 --> 00:14:22,940
the goats, and the sheep.

242
00:14:23,080 --> 00:14:26,440
Okay? Does that make
sense? So what we realize,

243
00:14:26,800 --> 00:14:30,460
what these people realize
is they can take the cows,

244
00:14:30,480 --> 00:14:33,400
the goats and the sheep,
from the farmers, okay?

245
00:14:33,500 --> 00:14:36,240
Because there was a lot of
trading back then, and then

246
00:14:36,240 --> 00:14:39,180
raise them in the steppes, and
because there's so much grass,

247
00:14:39,940 --> 00:14:41,180
they'll grow very fast.

248
00:14:41,520 --> 00:14:44,880
And then you can use that
as the source of your food.

249
00:14:45,040 --> 00:14:46,900
Okay? So they created a new economy.

250
00:14:48,020 --> 00:14:50,060
Well, then they, what
the second innovation is,

251
00:14:50,560 --> 00:14:52,740
well, then they realize is, you know what?

252
00:14:52,880 --> 00:14:55,120
We can also drink their milk.

253
00:14:55,320 --> 00:14:56,720
Okay? Dairy.

254
00:14:58,060 --> 00:15:01,860
And this is important because
